>Paradox-eliminating Rule Number 1: "If a convoyed army attacks a 
>fleet that is supporting an action in or into a body of water that 
>contains a convoying fleet, that support is not cut by the convoyed 
>army under any circumstance (but a convoying army does cut all other 
>supports normally)."
>
>Paradox-eliminating Rule Number 2: "If a situation arises in which 
>an army's convoy order results in a paradoxical adjudication, the 
>turn is adjudicated as if the convoying army had been ordered to 
>hold."


Just a thought - Why not add the following rule instead:

"For the purposes of resolving conflicts, a convoyed army acts as if 
attacking from the last fleet in it's convoy chain."

This would rather neatly (IMHO) solve the paradox, since support 
cannot be cut by a unit from the space you are supporting (Rule Ten, 
cutting support).  The french army would bounce, and the English and 
German fleets would stand off each other.  This wording would also 
allow you to convoy armies to cut other people's support, as well, 
which the current wording does not.

It's also good from a real world sense, too, since it doesn't 
introduce any new/strange elements into the game, it builds on 
already existing rules, and the wording is pretty straightforward.

Just my 2c worth :)

Anthony

